name: Horsehead_Nebula
text1: "Hubble Sees a Horsehead of a Different Color"
text2: "Backlit wisps along the Horsehead Nebula upper ridge are being illuminated by Sigma Orionis
text3: a young five-star system just off the top of this image from the Hubble Space Telescope."

name: Puzzling_Galaxy
text1: "This NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope image features a galaxy that’s hard to categorize. The galaxy in question is NGC 2775
text2: which lies 67 million light-years away in the constellation Cancer (the Crab). NGC 2775 sports a smooth
text3: featureless center that is devoid of gas
column8: resembling an elliptical galaxy. It also has a dusty ring with patchy star clusters
column9: like a spiral galaxy. Which is it: spiral or elliptical — or neither?"
column10: "Because we can only view NGC 2775 from one angle
column11: it’s difficult to say for sure. Some researchers classify NGC 2775 as a spiral galaxy because of its feathery ring of stars and dust
column12: while others classify it as a lenticular galaxy. Lenticular galaxies have features common to both spiral and elliptical galaxies."
column13: "Astronomers aren’t certain of exactly how lenticular galaxies come to be
column14: and they might form in a variety of ways. Lenticular galaxies might be spiral galaxies that merged with other galaxies
column15: or that have mostly run out of star-forming gas and lost their prominent spiral arms. They also might have started out more like elliptical galaxies
column16: then collected gas into a disk around them."
